data.title: He did it HER way: Definitive biography of Frank Sinatra tells of the dominating and unhinged mother whose ferocious ambition drove him to stardom
data.meta_description: Frank Sinatra left his wife of eleven years after meeting a girl who could drink and swear as hard as the only other woman in his life; his dominating mother.
data.text:
On A raw December afternoon in 1915, the kitchen of a flat in the Little Italy area of Hoboken, New Jersey, was full of women, all gathered around a table, all shouting at once.

On the table lay a copper-haired girl, just 19, moaning. Dolly Sinatras labour had stalled.

The midwife wiped the poor girls brow and sent urgently for the doctor.

When he arrived ten long minutes later, he clamped metallic forceps round the babys head.

Short-lived bliss: Frank marries the fiery Ava Gardner, the screen siren for whom he left his wife Nancy after 11 years

Then he pulled hard, hauling the child from its mothers womb and, in the violent process, tearing the left side of its face, neck and ear.

The doctor cut the cord and laid the boy - huge and blue, bleeding from his wounds, and apparently dead - by the kitchen sink, then quickly shifted his efforts to saving the nearly unconscious mothers life.

The women all leant in, shouting advice in Italian. At the back of the scrum, one of them looked at the seemingly lifeless baby, picked up it up and, just in case, ran ice cold water from the sink over it and slapped its back. It snuffled and began to howl.

Mother and child both survived, but neither ever forgot the brutality of that birth. Frank Sinatra  the superstar with a voice that would bewitch the world - bore the scars, both physical and psychological, to the end of his years.

Throughout his vastly documented life, he would avoid being photographed from his left.

One scar, hard to disguise (though frequently airbrushed), ran diagonally from the corner of his mouth to his jaw line.

His ear resembled an apricot run over by a steamroller. In childhood, a mastoid operation would leave another thick ridge of scar tissue on his neck, while in adolescence, severe acne left pockmarks on his skin.

As an adult, he would apply Max Factor Pan-Cake to his face and neck every morning and again after each of the several showers that, as a compulsive and obsessive hand and body washer, he took every day.

The worlds women might fall at his feet in adoration and long to be in his bed, but, in his own eyes, he was disfigured, a freak, the Scarface that his schoolmates in Hoboken taunted him with when he was a kid.

Even when he was in his early 40s, on top of the world and in the midst of an artistic outpouring unparalleled in the history of popular music, the birth trauma impinged on the great mans mind.

In a nightclub with a lover named Peggy Connelly, he flinched when, in the dark, she caressed his left cheek and her fingertips touched his ear. Though she had barely noticed the deformity, he told her how sensitive he was about it.

Then, unusually for him, he spilt the whole story  his birth weight (a massive 13lbs, the ripping forceps, the way hed been left for dead. They werent thinking about me, just about my mother, he said. They just ripped me out and tossed me aside.

Connelly recalled: There was no outburst of emotion, just a lingering bitterness about what he felt had been a stupid neglect of his infant self to concentrate on his mother, otherwise his torn ear might have been tended to in time.

As for his mother, the shadow of the domineering Dolly hung over him long into adulthood. She was a volcanic and unpredictable creature, a woman he seems to have hated and loved, avoided and sought out, in equal measures, throughout his life.

Early career: Frank started the singing career which would bring him such success in a local nightspot

But the truth was that her personality was uncomfortably similar to his own.

Dolly  a nickname acquired as a little girl for being so pretty  was loud, relentlessly foul-mouthed, brilliant (she had a natural facility for languages) and toweringly ambitious.

The mystery was why she hitched her wagon to Marty Sinatra, a good-natured but useless blockhead of a man. He was a bantamweight prize-fighter, short, with receding hair and tattooed arms.

His appearance was tough and threatening but inside he was sweet and dim.

Asthmatic and illiterate, he never said much. Frank recalled listening through the bedroom wall to his parents talking. Or rather shed be talking and hed be listening. All Id hear from him were grunts.

Marty came originally from Sicily, whereas Dollys people were from the north of Italy, near Genoa.

The ancient social prejudice on the part of northern Italians toward southerners makes it doubly difficult to imagine why, aged 16, she set her cap at him. Was it irresistible attraction? Or adolescent rebellion against her old-fashioned parents?

Little Dolly (she was under 5ft and weighed 6 st) would disguise herself as a boy to sneak into Martys prize-fights, her hair stuffed into a cap, a cigar stuck in her mouth. At her urging, the two eloped and married on Valentines Day 1913.

After Frank was born, there were no more babies, possibly because the birth rendered Dolly unable to have any, but more likely because she simply decided  and she was one of lifes deciders  she didnt want to go through that again.

But she compensated for her trauma in the strangest of ways. She chose to become a midwife and an abortionist, for which illegal activity she got the nickname Hatpin Dolly and a criminal record.

But businesslike Dolly had many other fish to fry in teeming Hoboken, just across the water from New York.

Her skill with Italian dialects and her fluency in English led to her to become a facilitator for new immigrants trying to get citizenship papers.

Two of a kind: Frank with his domineering mother in 1976

This work brought her to the attention of local Democratic Party politicians. Impressed by the force of her personality, they saw her as a natural leader in the community.

Soon she was getting out votes and campaigning for causes, all the while roaming the streets with her black midwifes bag.

Dolly had a politicians temperament  restless, energetic, unreflective. And, though she wasnt home much and regularly farmed little Frankie out to his grandmother or a nice Jewish neighbour, she had firm ideas about child rearing.

She paid him both too much attention and too little. Having wanted a girl, she dressed him in pink baby clothes and, once he was walking, in Little Lord Fauntleroy outfits.

When she was with him, she alternately coddled him and abused him.

The child was spirited and so was the mother. She once pushed him down a flight of stairs, knocking him unconscious. She regularly beat him with a stick. In those days it was known as discipline.

Macrophallus is the medical term, and Frank was proud of his extraordinary endowment

When I got out of hand, Sinatra recalled, she would give me a rap with that little club, then shed hug me to her breast.

He told the actress Shirley MacLaine: She scared the s*** outta me.

Both spoiled and neglected, praised to the skies and viciously cut down when he failed to please her, he grew up suffering an infinite neediness, an inability to be alone, and cycles of grandiosity and bottomless depression.

He learned never to trust anyone  especially her, the one in whom he should have been able to place ultimate trust.

Not surprisingly, he would feel ambivalent about women until the end of his days. He would show every lover  and there were many  something of what Dolly had shown him.

Sinatra the super-star liked to foster the impression that hed led a pretty rough-and-tumble childhood among the street gangs of Hoboken.

A heavy hand? Frank and his mother on a trip to the Catskill Mountains

More likely, he spent his early years dodging the jibes of the tough kids on his block, who found him spoiled and babyish. For all his later claims that he ran with a rough crowd when young and carried a length of lead pipe as a weapon, the accounts from his Hoboken contemporaries portray him as a little weakling who couldnt punch his way out of a paper bag.

An only child  unusual in Twenties America  he grew up a lonely boy, by turns timid and over-assertive. There was a rumour that he was still playing with dolls at the age of 12.

He desperately wanted to be part of a gang or group of any sort. He used the pocket money that Dolly  pretty well-off compared with her neighbours  gave him to try to buy friendship with gifts and treats. Yet he was mocked for his clothes, his oddity and his emotionalism. His anger and laughter and tears came too easily. He would never be one of the cool kids.

But, despite their derision, he always had a strong sense of being special, an air of entitlement he inherited from Dolly. She wanted and expected possessions and power.

So did he. Frank may have been uncertain about how to get along with his feisty, difficult mother, but he was absolutely sure that he had big things coming to him in his life, once he got the chance.

Streetwise: Frankie had a credit account at the local department store

Meanwhile, the whole family was moving upwards. Dolly and Marty bought a bar. Then she used her political connections to get her husband a job in the local fire department, no mean achievement given that the Hoboken fire service was (a) predominantly Irish and (b) required a written test of all applicants and Marty was illiterate.

But to Dolly Sinatra, no was an inaudible syllable and Marty became a fireman!

With him established in a rock-solid and well-paid job, they could now afford a leg-up into a house in a better part of town.

Here, at a time when entire families in Hoboken slept in a single room, Frank had not only his own bedroom but, luxury of luxuries, his own radio.

Radio was just coming into its own as a medium. Alone on his bed, young Frankie listened hungrily to opera, big bands and, above all, crooners such as Rudy Valle and his favourite, Bing Crosby. He longed to be able to sing like Bing and believed he could.

As he moved into early adolescence, Frank was increasingly aware of how much more sensitive he was than other kids.

Inside his head he was a riot of constantly flowing emotions  happy to sad to miserable to ecstatic to bored, sometimes all within the space of a minute.

He was ashamed of these feelings, thinking them girly, so he kept this part of himself to himself. He also kept secret the thrill he felt at the sound of Crosbys voice and his certainty that Bing was speaking directly to him.

He left school just before his 16th birthday, dropping out of his own volition (or, as he later claimed in another attempt to bolster his bad-boy credentials, being expelled for rowdiness).

Dolly, whod dreamed of her boy becoming a doctor or a civil engineer, was furious.

If you think youre going to be a goddamned loafer, youre crazy! she screamed at him.

Jaw firmly set, just as it was when she got Marty his job at the fire department, she went straight over to the offices of the local paper, the Jersey Observer, and buttonholed Frankies godfather, the circulation manager, to give him a job.

He got one, bundling newspapers, but he didnt think it was good enough for him, and nor did Dolly.

Frank fancied himself as a sportswriter, and one day, after a cub reporter was killed in a car crash, Dolly ordered her utterly unqualified son to take the job.

He was sitting at the dead boys desk when the editor saw him and threw him out, whereupon Frankie lost control.

Screaming, red faced, veins pounding, he dredged up every scrap of gutter talk hed ever learned. This was pure Dolly  and there would be many such volcanic exhibitions in Sinatras life.

Does this make him a tough guy after all? Probably not. An over-aggressive, loud-talking bantamweight, he snarled to hide his terrors  in this case, his fear of the drubbing he knew hed get from Dolly for being fired.

Still, he looked good. He was a natty dresser even then. He had a credit account at a local department store  thanks to Dolly  and was so well-tailored that his neighbourhood nickname changed from Scarface to Slacksey.

Frankie was so well-tailored that his neighbourhood nickname changed from 'Scarface' to 'Slacksey'

He was frequently seen not only smoking a pipe like his idol Bing, but also wearing a white yachting cap.

For all that he took what menial jobs he could find in factories and the dock, in his mind he was a personage. In the evenings, he sang at school dances, political clubs, taverns. Dolly helped out with her contacts.

His pretensions didnt sit well with a lot of people. Who the hell did he think he was, strutting around Hoboken in fancy duds and a yachting cap?

Even Dolly got fed up. When she saw Crosbys picture on Franks bedroom wall, she threw a shoe at her son and called him a bum. But gradually his parents grasped that he was dead set on singing as a career.

Dolly gave him $65  a great deal of money then  for a microphone and a small amplifier. With his yearning, boyish voice that melted every girl who heard it, he was determined to break into the music business.

Frank Sinatra continued his singing career up until his death in 1992 at the age of 82

He needed help from the usual source. Dolly leaned hard on the owner of a nightspot to give her son a regular singing job and for a while he crooned there five nights a week.

Then he heard that a singing trio of local Italian lads known as the Three Flashes were to be auditioned for a slot on a radio talent show, the X Factor of its day.

Frankie told his mother he desperately wanted to be the fourth Flash. She marched round to the other parents to remind them who she was and what she had done for them and that she would be very disappointed if her son were not included.He was in.

Amazingly, they won the contest, which gave them a place on a countrywide series of concerts by winners past and present.

Ava boozed and cussed like a sailor. She's a great broad, said Frank's mother

One week after their radio performance, they were on tour with a motley troupe of bell ringers, jug blowers, harmonica players and yodellers.

In town after town, Franks emotional voice was a sensation with the girls in the audiences. They gathered adoringly at the front of the orchestra during the show and waited for him afterwards.

Suddenly he was having lots of sex with lots of women  young ones mainly, but some older ones, too, including married ones whose husbands were out during the day.

He wasnt much to look at, what with the facial scars and the acne, though his mouth, with its slight up-curve at the corners and jutting lower lip, was beautifully formed. And his eyes  those ol blue eyes!  were a little bit wild.

He stood just 5ft 7 in (though over the years he would give his height variously as 5ft 9in, 5ft 10in, even 5ft 11in). He was also rake-thin  self-consciously so.

Throughout his life, he was ambivalent at best about his physical self  his height, his skinny behind, his facial scars, his receding, then vanishing, hairline.

But he made up for all this with the inordinate size of another part of his anatomy, which was so big, according to his valet in later life, that he had to have special underwear made to keep it in check.

Macrophallus is the medical term, and Frank was proud of his extraordinary endowment. He was prouder still of his voice. In his DNA, he carried an indefinable something composed of loneliness and need, infinite ambition and intelligence, all of it from Dolly.

Combined with his intense musicality, all this made him entirely different from every other singer.

She kept a watching eye on him as he struggled for success.

Once, fearing his Italian name was working against him, he proposed taking an anglicised stage name - Frankie Trent. When Dolly got wind of it, she gave him both barrels for even thinking of disowning his background.

A friend of Frank remembered seeing Dolly in his dressing room, a great big bossy lady, very domineering, scare you to death.

But she was the devil he knew and her influence was profound. Because of her, all his life he was drawn into the orbit of strong characters.

Frank once said that the only two people he was ever afraid of were his mother and the renowned big band leader Tommy Dorsey, for whom he sang and first made a name for himself.

It was meant as a joke, but it was a deeply significant one. Fear was a key part of his makeup, and in temperament, Dorsey, more feared than loved, was the spitting image of Dolly.

With both Dolly and Dorsey, the uncertainty of their affection and approval was sheer torture for him, but it must also have been thrilling, even sexually exciting.

Rumours of sado-masochistic tendencies always hovered around Sinatra and, given the power his mother and his mentor exercised over him, its not hard to see why.

Perhaps sado-masochism was also why he was drawn into the disastrous, doomed love affair that brought him to despair.

Dolly never much cared for Nancy, the sweet, Italian girl-next-door Frank married  at Dollys insistence, it must be said  at Our Lady of Sorrows Church in Jersey City when he was just 23.

But film and sex goddess Ava Gardner, for whom he left Nancy after 11 years of marriage and three children, was a different matter.

Ava drank and cussed like a sailor, and Dolly Sinatra, to her delight, could keep right up with her. At the same time, Ava was stupefyingly beautiful.

In her business life, Dolly had run across plenty of dirty girls with dirty mouths, yet with the pretty ones, butter mostly wouldnt melt.

But this one wore her gorgeousness so lightly, smoked her cigarettes so off-handedly, swore so fluently, and laughed so raucously that Dolly was as instantly smitten as her son.

After meeting Ava, Dolly pinched Franks skinny cheek and congratulated him on the great broad hed landed  and, as so often before in his life, he must have been grateful for her approval.

But, as we will see on Monday, Ava was so fiery and fear
